@article{ConnorKendall-2014,
abstract = {In this paper we describe a perfect simulation algorithm for the stable M/G/c queue. Sigman (2011) showed how to build a dominated coupling-from-the-past algorithm for perfect simulation of the super-stable M/G/c queue operating under first-come- first-served discipline. Sigman's method used a dominating process provided by the corresponding M/G/1 queue (using Wolff's sample path monotonicity, which applies when service durations are coupled in order of initiation of service). The method exploited the fact that the workload process for the M/G/1 queue remains the same under different queueing disciplines, in particular under the processor sharing discipline, for which a dynamic reversibility property holds. We generalise Sigman's construction to the stable case by comparing the M/G/c queue to a copy run under random assignment. This allows us to produce a na{\"{i}}ve perfect simulation algorithm based on running the dominating process back to the time it first empties. We also construct a more efficient algorithm that uses sandwiching by lower and upper processes constructed as coupled M/G/c queues started respectively from the empty state and the state of the M/G/c queue under random assignment. A careful analysis shows that appropriate ordering relationships can still be maintained, so long as service durations continue to be coupled in order of initiation of service. We summarise statistical checks of simulation output, and demonstrate that the mean run-time is finite so long as the second moment of the service duration distribution is finite.},
annote = {From Mathematical Reviews
The article describes two algorithms for perfect simulation of a stable M/G/c queue. It generalizes Sigman's method, which dominates an M/G/c queue with the corresponding M/G/1 queue, while coupling their service times in order of initiation of service. ("Domination'' here refers to inequalities that compare queues or queueing disciplines according to queue lengths, workloads, etc.) Sigman's coupling is useful, however, only when the M/G/1 queue is stable, or equivalently, only when a very restrictive hypothesis of super-stability for the M/G/c queue is in force. The present article generalizes Sigman's construction from super-stable to stable M/G/c queues by comparing an M/G/c queue to a copy under the random assignment discipline. The copy is then equivalent to c independent copies of an M/G/1 queue. The workload process for the M/G/c queue remains invariant under various queueing disciplines, in particular under the judicious choice of a processor-sharing discipline, which endows the copy with dynamic reversibility. A naive algorithm then runs the copy backward in time until the copy first regenerates by emptying. The algorithm then samples the (equilibrium) queueing state at time 0 ("coupling from the past''). Because of frequent practical interest in simulating queues with heavy traffic, the naive algorithm can be expensive, however. A second, more efficient coupling algorithm therefore sandwiches the M/G/c queue between lower and upper bounding queues. It then simulates backward in time until it can sample the equilibrium queueing state at time 0 unambiguously. An empirical assessment of the algorithms and a discussion of future directions for research conclude the article. Reviewed by John Lawrence Spouge},
