@article{BanerjeeKendall-2015,
abstract = {This is a case study concerning the rate at which probabilistic coupling occurs for nilpotent diffusions. We focus on the simplest case of Kolmogorov diffusion (Brownian motion together with its time integral or, more generally, together with a finite number of iterated time integrals). We show that in this case there can be no Markovian maximal coupling. Indeed, there can be no efficient Markovian coupling strategy (efficient for all pairs of distinct starting values), where the notion of efficiency extends the terminology of Burdzy and Kendall (2000). Finally, at least in the classical case of a single time integral, it is not possible to choose a Markovian coupling that is optimal in the sense of simultaneously minimizing the probability of failing to couple by time t for all positive t . In recompense for all these negative results, we exhibit a simple efficient non-Markovian coupling strategy.},
annote = {From Mathematical Reviews
Let B be a standard real-valued Brownian motion. A standard generalized Kolmogorov diffusion of index k is a vector-valued process I˜=(I˜0,I˜1,{\ldots},I˜k), defined recursively as 
I˜0(t)=B(t),I˜r(t)=∫t0I˜r−1(s)ds,r=1,2,{\ldots},k.
This paper studies probabilistic coupling in the class of Kolmogorov diffusions. In particular, it addresses the issues of maximal coupling, Markovian coupling, and efficient coupling as well as the coupling rate. 
   If T=inf{\{}t{\textgreater}0:Xs=X˜s for all s≥t{\}} is a coupling time of two coupled process X and X˜, then a coupling is called maximal if it simultaneously minimizes P(T{\textgreater}t) for all t{\textgreater}0. The paper starts with deriving the rate of maximal coupling: 
P(T{\textgreater}t)∼O(1tk+1/2).

   Generally, explicit constructions of maximal couplings are hard, in which case Markovian couplings may be a way to proceed. (Markovian couplings are the couplings that produce a joint process with marginals being transition probability kernels of the coupled diffusions.) The authors prove that, regrettably, in the case of Kolmogorov diffusion there can be no maximal Markovian coupling. 
   Next, the notion of efficient coupling is introduced, in the spirit and extending that of K. Burdzy and W. S. Kendall [Ann. Appl. Probab. 10 (2000), no. 2, 362–409; MR1768241]. It is then shown that no efficient Markovian coupling exists for the Kolmogorov diffusions. 
   In the last part, as a compensation for previous "negative'' discoveries, the authors construct a nice non-Markovian coupling strategy, called finite-look-ahead coupling, which does achieve efficiency. Reviewed by Gennady Shaikhet},
